cs.CV, cs.IT, cs.LG, cs.MS, cs.MM 

The paper presents a novel algorithm for the registration of pulmonary CT scans, which involves integrating sparse keypoint correspondences into a dense continuous optimization framework. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category, as it deals with image registration and alignment. Additionally, the paper employs regularization and control mechanisms to prevent foldings of the deformation grid and restrict the determinant of the Jacobian to physiologically meaningful values, which suggests that it may also belong to the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The paper also uses adaptive weighting and matrix-free derivative calculation schemes, which suggests that it may belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) and mathematical software (cs.MS) sub-categories, respectively. Finally, the paper deals with medical imaging and analysis, which suggests that it may also belong to the multimedia (cs.MM) sub-category.
